Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) - project example

Martin Frigaard

Intro

This R Markdown document template for your exploratory data analysis project. Youve selected (or youve been assigned) a dataset, and youre going to use this template to import, wrangle, visualize and communicate the contents of your data.

Background

You should have your project set up using the goodenuffR package. If you havent, install this package using the code below:

install.packages("devtools")# for install_github()
library(devtools) # load devtools
devtools::install_github("mjfrigaard/goodenuffR") # install goodenuffR
library(goodenuffR) # load goodenuffR

Recall you can use the goodenuffR functions to create specific files in your project:

goodenuffR::goodenuff_code() # create code/ folder and files
goodenuffR::goodenuff_data() # create data/ folder and data/raw folder
goodenuffR::goodenuff_doc() # create documentation files
goodenuffR::goodenuff_results() # create results folder 
goodenuffR::goodenuff_collab() # create CITATION, requirements, etc.

Lets get started!

Packages

The packages below have been covered in the course slides and exercises. Youre not required to know all the details of every package (we can look that up), but you do need to know how to install a package.

library(tidyverse) # for dplyr, tidyr, ggplot2 and others
library(janitor) # for names 
library(skimr) # basic data summaries

Import

Use the code chunk below to import your data into RStudio. The example we will use is from this pudding article, A People Map of the US.

# this will import data in a .csv file, other options include readxl and 
# googlesheets4, and vroom
PeopleMapRaw <- readr::read_csv(file = "https://bit.ly/3mBWNsd")

Dimensions and structure

We will start by asking some general questions about the dataset structure and shape.

How many columns?

How many rows?

To simply print the number of rows in your dataset, you can use nrow()

Export raw data

Now that we know our data imported correctly, we can export an example of these data to the data/raw/ folder.

fs::dir_create("data/raw/")
out_path <- paste0("data/raw/", noquote(lubridate::today()), "-PeopleMapRaw.csv")
write_csv(x = PeopleMapRaw, file = out_path)
# verify
fs::dir_tree("data/raw/")

##  2021-10-30-PeopleMapRaw.csv
##  2021-10-31-PeopleMapRaw.csv

Wrangle

The first thing we want to do with PeopleMapRaw is standardize the column names and make sure theyre meaningful, then we want to check the contents of each variable.

Column names

The janitor package has a great function for dealing with column names, janitor::clean_names(). This function automatically converts all names to lower_snake_case, which makes them easier to read and program with.

In PeopleMapRaw, the names are already in lower_snake_case, but well apply clean_names() just because its a good habit to get into.

PeopleMap <- janitor::clean_names(PeopleMapRaw)
glimpse(PeopleMap)
## Rows: 9,375
## Columns: 11
## $ name         <chr> "Donald Trump", "Donald Trump", "Cardi B", "Cardi B", "
## $ city         <chr> "Bedminster", "New York City", "Edgewater", "Bronx", "S
## $ neighborhood <chr> NA, NA, NA, NA, NA, NA, NA, NA, NA, NA, "Bushwick", NA,
## $ place        <chr> "Bedminster", "New York City", "Edgewater", "Bronx", "S

## $ views_sum    <dbl> 140255718, 140641448, 28729507, 29101434, 42213949, 425
## $ name_clean   <chr> "Donald Trump", "Donald Trump", "Cardi B", "Cardi B", "

Notice I changed the name of PeopleMapRaw to PeopleMap because weve altered the contents of the raw data (and we want to keep these separate).

We should inspect this output for anything that looks out of the ordinary. For example, we can see state lists 93 unique values. This isnt possible, so we should check this variable with count()

PeopleMap %>% 
  count(state, sort = TRUE)

We can see this is including more than just the states (counties too). Were going to wrangle the state to state_name (and not remove any of the other information in state).

R comes with a vector state.name which contains all 50 state names.

Well convert this to a regular expression.

# get a regular expression for state names 
state_pattern <- paste0(state.name, collapse = "|")
state_pattern
## [1] "Alabama|Alaska|Arizona|Arkansas|California|Colorado|Connecticut|Delaware|Florida|Georgia|Hawaii|Idaho|Illinois|Indiana|Iowa|Kansas|Kentucky|Louisiana|Maine|Maryland|Massachusetts|Michigan|Minnesota|Mississippi|Missouri|Montana|Nebraska|Nevada|New Hampshire|New Jersey|New Mexico|New York|North Carolina|North Dakota|Ohio|Oklahoma|Oregon|Pennsylvania|Rhode Island|South Carolina|South Dakota|Tennessee|Texas|Utah|Vermont|Virginia|Washington|West Virginia|Wisconsin|Wyoming"

Well use state_pattern to filter the states in the state column to only actual states, then count the two variables to see if there are any valuess that were missed.

PeopleMap %>% 
  mutate(
  state_name = case_when(
    str_detect(state, state_pattern) ~ state,
    TRUE ~ NA_character_)) %>% 
    count(state_name, state) %>% 
    filter(!is.na(state_name)) %>% 
    arrange(n)

We will add the Iowa County and Washington County to the mutate function (to properly categorize the counties as NA)

PeopleMap %>% 
  mutate(
  state_name = case_when(
    str_detect(state, state_pattern) ~ state,
    TRUE ~ NA_character_),
  # include the counties
  state_name = case_when(
     state_name == "Iowa County" ~ NA_character_,
     state_name == "Washington County" ~ NA_character_, 
     TRUE ~ state_name)) %>% 
  count(state_name, state) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(state_name)) %>% 
  arrange(n)

Now we will create a state_abbr (state abbreviation) variable based on our new state_name variable using the state2abbr() from the usdata package.

# install.packages("usdata")
library(usdata) 
PeopleMap <- PeopleMap %>% 
  mutate(
  state_name = case_when(
    str_detect(state, state_pattern) ~ state,
    TRUE ~ NA_character_),
  # include the counties
  state_name = case_when(
     state_name == "Iowa County" ~ NA_character_,
     state_name == "Washington County" ~ NA_character_, 
     TRUE ~ state_name), 
  state_abbr = usdata::state2abbr(state = state_name)) 
PeopleMap %>% 
  select(state, state_name, state_abbr) %>% head()
PeopleMap %>% 
  select(state, state_name, state_abbr) %>% tail()

Visualizations

Were going to create a few exploratory graphs of the variables in our imported data. From the skim() output, we can see there are four numerical variables and seven character variables.

Single variable graphs

Were going to start with some graphs of the numerical variable, views_median.

# label
labs_hist <- labs(title = "Histogram of PeopleMap$views_median", 
                  x = "Median Views")
PeopleMap %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = views_median)) + 
    geom_histogram() + 
      labs_hist

# label
labs_freq <- labs(title = "Histogram of PeopleMap$views_median", 
                  x = "Median Views")
PeopleMap %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = views_median)) + 
    geom_freqpoly() + 
      labs_freq

Multiple variable graphs

Were going to see how views_median looks across the state_name variable.

labs_box2 <- labs(
     title = "Median views by state",
     subtitle = "source: https://github.com/the-pudding/data",
     fill = "State",
     x = "Median page views",
     y = "State")
PeopleMap %>%  
  # remove missing states
  filter(!is.na(state_name)) %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = views_median, 
                      y = state_name, 
                      fill = state_name),
                      alpha = 1/5, 
               show.legend = FALSE) + 
  labs_box2

The graph above makes it hard to see the difference between states, so we can use the facet_wrap() function by setting the group aesthetic to our new state_name variable.

labs_freq2 <- labs(
     title = "Median views by state",
     subtitle = "source: https://github.com/the-pudding/data",
     fill = "State",
     x = "Median page views",
     y = "State")
PeopleMap %>% 
  # remove missing states
  filter(!is.na(state_name)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = views_median, group = state_name)) + 
    geom_freqpoly(aes(color = state_name), 
                  show.legend = FALSE) + 
    facet_wrap(~ state_name) + 
    labs_freq2

This is a better way to see which states had more median page views, but we can still improve the graph by using our state_abbr variable, the geofacet package and black and white theme (theme_bw()) from ggplot2.

library(geofacet)
PeopleMap %>% 
  # remove missing states
  filter(!is.na(state_abbr)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = views_median, group = state_abbr)) + 
    geom_freqpoly(aes(color = state_abbr), 
                  show.legend = FALSE) + 
    facet_geo(~ state_abbr) + 
  theme_bw() + 
  labs_freq2

Data dictionary

We want to include a data dictionary with this dataset, which we can find in the README.md file on the Github page.

Example

This folder contains all of the data used in The Pudding essay A People Map of the US published in May 2019.

The data will never be updated.

Below youll find the metadata for each file.

people-map.csv

  • What is this?: Data of the most visited person(s) Wikipedia page for each city with a List of People from (~ 10,000) in the US
  • Source(s) & Methodology: English Wikipedia
  • Last Modified: May 2019
  • Contact Information: Russell Goldenberg
  • Spatial Applicability: United States
  • Temporal Applicability: July 2015 through May 2019
  • Observations (Rows): Each row represents one person.
  • Variables (Columns):
Header Description Data Type
name name of person text
city city/town name text
neighborhood neighborhood name (if applicable) text
place neighborhood or city text
views_median average number of pageviews per day number
views_sum total number of pageviews number
name_clean display name (removed items in parenthesis) text
lat latitude of place number
lng longitude of place number
extract 200 character description of person text
state state (or sometimes county if state is NA) text
state_name state name text
state_abbr state abbreviated name text
